2. HER FLOWERS IN NEEDLEWORK.

ln early spring, when the beauteous Seton saw the first flowers on the enamelled mead, she took her needle and traced on linen Flora's footsteps. There you behold Iris and the Poppy and the tender Crocus, Violets in blue . and purple and gold; white Lilies with yellow King-cups, and Tulips like a sun or stars. The Rose is there, both red and ivorywhite-resembling, the one, her snowy neck, the other her rosy lips; so also the columbine, the Hyacinth‚ the Flos Adonis, and eke the Narcissus. Place flowers of Nature and of the Setonian needle side by side: any eye will avouch that both are real, or, if painted, painted by the same hand.
